<br>
Actually that's not far off point.  That's a decent example.  Airport security pre and post 9/11 is all about filling in gaps.  Somebody manages to sneak a gun through using a laptop, they start scanning laptops, etc.  The people who want to get things through find loopholes and only once we find out about it are those loopholes closed.  This kid pointed out holes by taking advantage of them and now they can correct them.  If a terrorist had done it and hijacked another plane we'd be saying &quot;Why didnt they think to tighten that up?&quot; and be in outrage.  Now whatever gaps he manipulated will be examined and he did it all while not posing a danger to a single person.  Is he technically guilty of a crime?  Yes.  But so were protestors of the 70s.  Just because you go against policy doesn't necessarily make your point any less valid.  That's what I'm saying.  They can make an example of this kid all they want but the only thing that tells me is that the powers that be expect to be able to run things their way without question and when they fuck up, then oh well, now they can fix it.  Bullshit.  I won't accept that and I'm glad that a few out there are smart enough and gutsy enough to take those risks to make the world a bit safer for the rest of us.  I dont think anyone would bitch if they had been the one on the plane that might have gotten hijacked again due to figuring out the hole that this kid has exposed.  But because some egos are burned and some people's shitty jobs are exposed, let's burn the kid.  It's BS and I hope the kid gets off. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><br>
